# Deploy Safety

`main` auto-deploys to Vercel. A commit that fails `astro build` becomes a
failed Vercel deployment (and an email). Never push code to `main` without a
green build.

## This machine cannot be trusted to build locally

The repo lives on OneDrive on Windows. Two known, recurring failures:

- Node child processes spawned from the embedded Cursor terminal die with
  `AssignProcessToJobObject: (6) The handle is invalid.` — so `astro build`,
  `npm ci`, and `esbuild`'s postinstall intermittently fail before the site
  even compiles. This is an environment bug, NOT a code bug. Do not interpret
  it as a build error.
- OneDrive file locks cause `EBUSY` / `EPERM` during `npm ci`.
- Large `git diff` / `git diff --stat` output is sometimes dropped or garbled
  by the embedded terminal. Do NOT diagnose build/syntax errors from a single
  `git diff` here — confirm by reading the actual file (and `git show HEAD:<path>`
  into a file, then read it) before claiming a file is broken.

## How to actually verify a build

1. Preferred: rely on the GitHub Actions **Build check** workflow
   (`.github/workflows/build.yml`), which runs `npm ci && npm run build` on
   every push and PR to `main`. If it is red, the Vercel deploy will also fail.
2. Or run `npm ci && npm run build` in a standalone Windows Terminal /
   PowerShell (outside Cursor), where Node runs reliably.

Never imply a deploy will succeed based only on lint or a local Cursor-shell
build attempt.

## Keep the working tree a single source of truth

- Do not commit local-only folders: `hyrox-guide-live-iteration/` (a full
  duplicate of this project), `Content for driving traffic/`, `Performance data/`.
  They are gitignored.
- Line endings are normalised to LF via `.gitattributes`. If many files show
  as "modified" with only CRLF→LF differences, that is line-ending churn, not
  real edits — clear it with `git restore <files>` / `git add --renormalize .`,
  do not treat it as content to review or commit.
